<PageLayout
  title="How to Redact Secrets From Prompt Logs"
  description="Redact API keys, personal data and internal identifiers from LLM prompt logs without destroying the message structure needed for debugging."
  h1="How to Redact Secrets From Prompt Logs"
  path="/guides/redact-secrets-from-prompt-logs"
  article
  published="2026-07-20"
  updated="2026-07-20"
>
  <p>
    Prompt logs combine several sensitive surfaces in one place: authorization data, customer text,
    internal instructions, tool results and database identifiers. Before a trace goes into a ticket,
    chat or public issue, redact it in a way that protects the data while preserving the structure
    needed to reproduce the bug.
  </p>

  <blockquote>
    <strong>Redaction rule:</strong> replace values, not structure. Keep field names, message order,
    data types and approximate lengths whenever they matter to the failure.
  </blockquote>

  <h2>Work on a copy and keep the original access-controlled</h2>
  <p>
    Store the raw trace only in the approved logging or incident system. Make a separate working copy
    for redaction and label it clearly. Do not overwrite the only evidence: exact whitespace,
    escaping or a malformed value may be important later.
  </p>
  <p>
    Format the working copy with the <a href="/prompt/">LLM Request Inspector</a>. Because processing
    happens in the browser, the site does not need to receive the log. Browser-only formatting reduces
    exposure, but it does not make the content safe to paste into a public channel—you must still
    remove sensitive values.
  </p>

  <h2>Remove credentials before anything else</h2>
  <p>
    Credentials are the highest-priority data because exposure can create immediate access. Search
    both keys and values; a copied request may include credentials in headers, query parameters,
    environment dumps or tool output.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>API keys and bearer tokens</li>
    <li>Session cookies and signed URLs</li>
    <li>OAuth access and refresh tokens</li>
    <li>Database connection strings</li>
    <li>Webhook signing secrets</li>
    <li>Private keys and service-account documents</li>
  </ul>
  <pre><code>{`"authorization": "Bearer [REDACTED_API_TOKEN]"
"database_url": "[REDACTED_CONNECTION_STRING]"`}</code></pre>
  <p>
    If a real credential has already been shared outside its intended boundary, redaction is not
    enough. Revoke or rotate it according to the provider’s incident procedure.
  </p>

  <h2>Replace personal data with stable placeholders</h2>
  <p>
    Use consistent placeholders so relationships remain visible. If the same email appears in three
    messages, replace it with the same token each time. Randomly deleting values can hide the fact
    that two records were incorrectly joined.
  </p>
  <pre><code>{`"customer_name": "[PERSON_1]"
"email": "[EMAIL_1]"
"account_id": "[ACCOUNT_1]"
"shipping_address": "[ADDRESS_1]"`}</code></pre>
  <p>
    Preserve the value type. Replace a numeric user ID with another number or a clearly typed token
    that the reproduction code accepts. If length or character set is part of the bug, record those
    properties separately rather than retaining the original value.
  </p>

  <h2>Review system prompts and retrieved context</h2>
  <p>
    A system prompt may expose internal policies, product logic or unpublished instructions even when
    it contains no personal data. Retrieved documents may include contracts, support conversations or
    proprietary source text. Decide whether the recipient needs the full content to understand the
    issue.
  </p>
  <p>
    When the wording is not relevant, replace a block with a descriptive marker such as
    <code>[INTERNAL_POLICY: 1,240 characters]</code>. Keep the full block only in the restricted
    incident record.
  </p>

  <h2>Do not forget tool calls and tool results</h2>
  <p>
    Tool results are often more sensitive than the user message. They may contain database rows,
    search results, file paths, shell output or third-party API responses. Expand every tool block and
    inspect nested objects before sharing the trace.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Redact filesystem usernames and private repository paths.</li>
    <li>Remove environment variables and command output containing tokens.</li>
    <li>Replace customer records with typed placeholders.</li>
    <li>Keep tool names and argument shapes when they explain the failure.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Preserve the failure condition</h2>
  <p>
    Over-redaction can make a reproduction useless. If the bug depends on a newline, Unicode
    character, deeply nested object or unusually long string, preserve that property with synthetic
    data. For example, replace a private 8,000-character document with generated text of the same
    length and structure.
  </p>
  <p>
    Compare the raw and redacted versions locally with the <a href="/diff/">Text Diff Checker</a>.
    Confirm that every sensitive value changed and that required message boundaries, field names and
    types stayed intact. Do not use a shareable diff URL for private data because the compared text is
    encoded into that URL.
  </p>

  <h2>Run a final disclosure review</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>Search for authorization headers, token prefixes and private-key markers.</li>
    <li>Search for email addresses, phone numbers, names and account identifiers.</li>
    <li>Inspect every system message, tool call and tool result.</li>
    <li>Check URLs for signed parameters and identifiers.</li>
    <li>Confirm placeholders are consistent across the trace.</li>
    <li>Ask whether the chosen destination is appropriate for the remaining content.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Prefer a redacted reproduction over a production trace</h2>
  <p>
    The safest debugging artifact is usually a minimal synthetic request that still fails. Use the
    redacted trace to understand the structure, then rebuild the case with invented users, documents
    and identifiers. This creates an example that is easier to share, test and keep in regression
    fixtures.
  </p>
  <p>
    After redaction, return to the <a href="/guides/debug-llm-request-payload/">LLM request debugging
    workflow</a> to verify message order, tool argument types and escaping without exposing the
    original production data.
  </p>
</PageLayout>
